This PR addresses two project goals - configuration and embedding.
### Embedding

We now expose a global function called `ramdaRepl` which takes two arguments - a reference to a target DOM node (such as a `<code>` block in the docs that we want to replace with a repl) - and a configuration object.

On application, the target DOM node is hidden and `ramdaRepl` will construct the DOM for the REPL and inject it as a sibling.

To demonstrate this, I've removed the repl HTML from `index.html` and replaced it with a target `<code>` element, similar to what we have on the Ramda doc pages. Clicking it will replace it with a repl instance.

The DOM structure for the repl is now declared as a JSON-like tree in `lib/js/dom/structure.js` and is converted into DOM nodes by `lib/js/dom/constructDOM.js`. Once this is complete it is put in the document and has the event handlers hooked up.
### Configuration

As per #9, the code relating to reading / updating the document fragment has been taken out and can be re-implemented using the `config` object (the second argument to `ramdaRepl`) - see example.

Additionally, the URLs for the API key and the return address are also passed in using the same object. Given either of these urls is not present, the shortlink control will not be shown.
### Example config

```
ramdaRepl(targetNode, {

  apiUrl: 'https://www.googleapis.com/urlshortener/v1/url?key=AIzaSyDhbAvT5JqkxFPkoeezJp19-S_mAJudxyk',
  returnUrl: 'http://ramdajs.com/repl/',

  // If unset, initialValue will use the value or textcontent of the
  // target element.
  initialValue: URI.decode(window.location.hash).substring(2),

  // Called with the pre-compiled content whenever it is changed.
  onChange : function(code) {
    // Here we can update the address
    window.location.hash = '?' + URI.encode(code);
  }

});
```
